data.content:
MSTest has a built-in `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods that give clearer failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's an improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use Assert.IsTrue with a message for predicate checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | You already check for 3, so `> 0` is redundant |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Failure message shows both values |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and message |

**Also available — `CollectionAssert`:**

```csharp
// All elements satisfy a condition
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// Check contents regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Check contents and order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Check an item exists
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** avoid `Assert.IsTrue` unless there's no specific assertion available — specific assertions produce much better failure diagnostics.
